76561197994399663,Recommended,265610,16665863,"Posted: 23 June, 2015",all,Sparkly Bear,"The ""overwhelmingly positive"" review score makes me think of the first Dim-Sum restaurant to recieve a Michelin star. That is to say it's not the most extravagant or artistic game, but an expert execution of some basic JRPG principles.I've already played it from start to finish for free online, and felt it was worth actually buying. From a replayability standpoint the humor and plot obviously doesn't hold up well, but the combat is still engrossing, and what more can you ask of something titled ""Epic Battle Fantasy""? The soundtrack is shockingly good in a nostalgic synthisizer sort of way, and though the tracks loop fairly heavily after 11 hours and counting I haven't muted it yet. The most impressive part for me is the level design. From start to finish you are never asked to backtrack without being rewarded for it. Exploration is heavily encouraged, and plot based roadblocks flow exceptionally nicely and naturally. Like Morrowind each 'tile' of the map is filled with side-quests and secrets to discover."
